metadata.name: Poems in the Public Domain #220
metadata.description:
POEMS IN THE PUBLIC DOMAIN [PITPD] represents a new form of poetic anthology—one that celebrates the role of the reader in shaping the life of a poem. In this unique art piece, 14 readers take turns discovering 30 classic poems. We invite collectors to explore this compendium, selected to present a diverse, engaging archive that acknowledges the importance of certain seminal works in shaping our collective unconscious. 

Inspired by Roland Barthe's maxim, "those who fail to reread are obliged to read the same story everywhere," each reader is represented by multiple pen colors & new marginalia, suggesting the crucial act of rereading. 

The verses vanish, just like our memory of their exact words might fade, but distilled, standout moments of personal connection remain. In time, even these wane, providing a scarcely perceptible backdrop as the poem is discovered & interpreted anew. 

PITPD explores authorship. When a poem enters the public domain, it no longer belongs to its author but to its readers. In the intimate moments we read a poem, we link it to our private, pulsating worlds & help ensure others will read it, too. If history’s palms hadn’t held Sappho’s words, our fingers wouldn’t hold them now. 

Readers write poetry’s survival. 

Each iteration of PITPD traces a narrative that can play for hours without repeating. Some 89% of iterations chronicle the life of a single poem, while 11% include multiple poems, intentionally surveying intertextuality. Taking advantage of the generative medium, embodied readership is represented via dynamic handwriting, dancing markings, algorithmic paper aging, coded stains, & other effects.

Spacebar pauses & resumes the animation. Refreshing the browser window restarts it. For those interested in the underlying code, please open the browser console. This collection’s ciphers, too, are in the public domain.

Additional information can be found in the companion article on fx(text): fxhash.xyz/article/poems-in-the-public-domain-marginalia-as-living-verse

metadata.name: Nounfall #92
metadata.description:
Nounfall is drawn exclusively from the 234 heads and 21 glasses that are used to build the current Nouns collection. The background colors are all pulled from the blessed Noun palette.

This is ok because Nouns are CC0, which basically means public domain. Check out nouns.wtf for more info.

They make for fun social media banners when cropped, if you wanna show off you fandom of Nouns.

C : Clear screen and start animation over
S : Save current image
1 -> 6 : Set pixel density to the respective number

So, if you want a high resolution file, tap `6` for it to redraw, and then `S` to save. You can also save while it's animating if you like, which is fun too.

metadata.name: GEN XYZ Das Occult #7106
metadata.description:
A 10k Generative Profile Pic collection
GEN XYZ Das Occult - by culla - @tamccullough

move over cryptopunks
there is a new group on the scene

100% code - not an image composition

A bunch of common palettes
A selection of rare palettes
And a smaller set of ultra rare palettes
However, rarity will be based on what combinations the code produces

The majority of tokens will not have a special trait
However your token might have one or even multiple special traits
But, be aware that only the last special trait added will be listed in the features

Even then, look closely, because not all aspects of the canvas are included in the features. Collectors should still look closely and choose what they like when buying on secondary.

Which team are you on? X or O?

follow culla on twitter for updates. Or maybe __acolyte__

If the non reserved tokens mint out quickly, Access List mints will have 24 hours to mint reserves assigned to those wallets

Thank you for supporting an emerging artist in the generative art space

Access List reserves were given to holders of the following PFP collections created by culla
2x for each Basqunk held
1x for each Inkspunk, TwoFourQunk, V0iD, DeeManz, Punkasso and CR0$$KULL
You would have needed to transfer the above tokens to your mint wallet at the time of the snapshot

share your tokens on social media with #genxyznft
Made with love by culla using p5.js

metadata.name: Colorfall #83
metadata.description:
My first attempt at a generative NFT. This started with an idea to create a grid of diagonal lines with the basic line function of p5js. I had discarded this idea until my friend said it looked like a waterfall of colors and he liked it, so I decided to mint it. After tweaking some parameters like colors and line thickness it produced some nice outputs.

I hope you will enjoy it. Free mint(unless you cant wait and want to pay =) plus 25% royalties for minters.

reserves for the collectors of my testnft on objkt, my friend CampendonkP and a few artists who I remembered who did free mints, like punevyr and JohnRising.

metadata.name: Pastoral Palettes #16
metadata.description:
Pastoral Palettes showcases 93 beautiful hand tuned palettes in a generative pastoral setting. The palettes themselves pay homage to great paintings from the past up to the present. Isolating the palettes in this way brings out the artistic genius of the underlying artwork in a unique way. The palette name in the features contains the painting and artist.

The algorithmic parts of Pastoral Palettes use many techniques to create the scene and generate the ground, sky, trees, and shrubbery. Using random perlin noise for the placement ensures a more natural looking scene. The sky is a gradient composed from the palette. Each blade of grass is drawn individually using perlin noise to create the color pattern in the grass. Each tree and shrub is randomly constructed and colored using color blending in the transition colors. The grass generation is the most computationally expensive and the density can be adjusted with the arrow keys, see below.

The mint size is relatively small in relation to the number of palettes, so to ensure that all palettes get generated at least once, we are including 2 palettes for each mint.

Each mint of Pastoral Palettes comes with sunlight and moonlight views, toggled with the 'f' key. The palettes look strikingly different for each view - you can choose which one you like best.

Variations:

 - Each palette has an equal chance of being minted. Since the mint size is so small compared to the number of palettes, there is a high chance of getting a rare palette. 
 - 2% chance of getting 5 palettes instead of the default of 2. 
 - 10% chance of getting a sun/moon in the sky.
 - Each layout will be entirely unique.

Pastoral Palettes is responsive and looks great on any size display. They look especially good on large displays of 2K, 4K, and even 8K.

'f' flips between sunlight and moonlight views.
'p' cycles through the palettes.
's' saves an image in the exact size of the current display.
'up/down arrow' adjusts the grass density. Denser grass may look better at some resolutions, but takes considerably longer to render, particularly on large displays.
